{"title_page": "Nassogne", "text_new": "{{Infobox Belgium municipality\n|name=Nassogne\n|picture=Nassogne JPG02.jpg\n|picture-legend=\n|map=Nassogne Luxembourg Belgium Map.png\n|map-legend=Location of Nassogne in Luxembourg province\n|arms=Blason de Nassogne.svg\n|flag\n|region={{BE-REG-WAL}}\n|community={{BE-FR}}\n|province={{BE-PROV-LX}}\n|arrondissement=[[Arrondissement of Marche-en-Famenne|Marche-en-Famenne]]\n|nis=83040\n|pyramid-date=\n|0-19=\n|20-64=\n|65=\n|foreigners=\n|foreigners-date=\n|mayor=Marcel Sepul (CDH)\n|majority=[[Centre D\u00e9mocrate Humaniste|CDH]], [[Socialist Party (francophone Belgium)|PS]]\n|postal-codes=6950-6953\n|telephone-area=084\n|web=[http://www.nassogne.be nassogne.be]\n|coordinates = {{coord|50|08|N|05|21|E|region:BE|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Nassogne''' is a [[Wallonia|Walloon]] [[municipality]] of [[Belgium]] located in the [[Luxembourg (province of Belgium)|province of Luxembourg]].\n\nOn 1 January 2007 the municipality, which covers 111.96&nbsp;km\u00b2, had 5,045 inhabitants, giving a [[population density]] of 45.1 inhabitants per km\u00b2.\n\n==Villages and towns==\n* [[Ambly]]\n* [[Bande, Belgium|Bande]]\n* [[Forri\u00e8res]]\n* [[Grune, Belgium|Grune]]\n* [[Harsin, Belgium|Harsin]]\n* [[Lesterny]]\n* [[Masbourg]]\n* [[Mormont, Nassogne|Mormont]]\n* Nassogne proper\n\n[[Image:Nassogne JPG01.jpg|thumb|none|272px|Nassogne: near St Monon's church]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of protected heritage sites in Nassogne]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.nassogne.be/ Official website] (in French)\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Nassogne\n|N  = [[Marche-en-Famenne]]\n|E  = [[La Roche-en-Ardenne]]<br/>[[Tenneville]]\n|S  = [[Saint-Hubert, Belgium|Saint-Hubert]]\n|SW = [[Tellin]]\n|W  = [[Rochefort, Belgium|Rochefort]] ([[Namur (province)|WNA]])\n}}\n{{Municipalities in Luxembourg}}\n\n[[Category:Nassogne| ]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Luxembourg (Belgium)]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Luxembourg (Belgium)]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Belgium]]\n\n\n{{LuxembourgBE-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Belgium municipality\n|name=Nassogne\n|picture=Nassogne JPG02.jpg\n|picture-legend=\n|map=Nassogne Luxembourg Belgium Map.png\n|map-legend=Location of Nassogne in Luxembourg province\n|arms=Blason de Nassogne.svg\n|flag\n|region={{BE-REG-WAL}}\n|community={{BE-FR}}\n|province={{BE-PROV-LX}}\n|arrondissement=[[Arrondissement of Marche-en-Famenne|Marche-en-Famenne]]\n|nis=83040\n|pyramid-date=\n|0-19=\n|20-64=\n|65=\n|foreigners=\n|foreigners-date=\n|mayor=Marcel Sepul (CDH)\n|majority=[[Centre D\u00e9mocrate Humaniste|CDH]], [[Socialist Party (francophone Belgium)|PS]]\n|postal-codes=6950-6953\n|telephone-area=084\n|web=[http://www.nassogne.be nassogne.be]\n|coordinates = {{coord|50|08|N|05|21|E|region:BE|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Nassogne''' is a [[Wallonia|Walloon]] [[municipality]] of [[Belgium]] located in the [[Luxembourg (province of Belgium)|province of Luxembourg]].\n\nOn 1 January 2007 the municipality, which covers 111.96&nbsp;km\u00b2, had 5,045 inhabitants, giving a [[population density]] of 45.1 inhabitants per km\u00b2.\n\n==Villages and towns==\n* [[Ambly]]\n* [[Bande]]\n* [[Forri\u00e8res]]\n* [[Grune, Belgium|Grune]]\n* [[Harsin, Belgium|Harsin]]\n* [[Lesterny]]\n* [[Masbourg]]\n* [[Mormont, Nassogne|Mormont]]\n* Nassogne proper\n\n[[Image:Nassogne JPG01.jpg|thumb|none|272px|Nassogne: near St Monon's church]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of protected heritage sites in Nassogne]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n*[http://www.nassogne.be/ Official website] (in French)\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Nassogne\n|N  = [[Marche-en-Famenne]]\n|E  = [[La Roche-en-Ardenne]]<br/>[[Tenneville]]\n|S  = [[Saint-Hubert, Belgium|Saint-Hubert]]\n|SW = [[Tellin]]\n|W  = [[Rochefort, Belgium|Rochefort]] ([[Namur (province)|WNA]])\n}}\n{{Municipalities in Luxembourg}}\n\n[[Category:Nassogne| ]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of Luxembourg (Belgium)]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Luxembourg (Belgium)]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Belgium]]\n\n\n{{LuxembourgBE-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "DrVogel", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nassogne"}
{"title_page": "Rebecca Adamson", "text_new": "{{short description|Cherokee-American businessperson and activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rebecca Adamson\n| image              = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1950}}\n| birth_place        = [[Akron, Ohio]], United States\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[Americans|American]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Southern New Hampshire University]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Businesswoman, advocate\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = Founding First Peoples Worldwide\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n'''Rebecca Adamson''' (born 1950)<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography Center|url=https://nationalwomenshistoryalliance.org/biographies/|publisher=National Women's History Project|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[Cherokee]] [[businessperson]] and [[advocate]]. She is former director, former president, and founder of [[First Nations Development Institute]] and the founder of First Peoples Worldwide.<ref name=Dartmouth>{{cite news|title=Dartmouth Honorary Degrees 2004:Rebecca L. Adamson|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~news/releases/2004/05/04a.html|publisher=Dartmouth News|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in Akron, Ohio, to a Swedish American father and a Cherokee mother, Adamson grew up in Akron and spent summers with her Cherokee grandmother in [[Lumberton, North Carolina]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Rebecca Adamson |url=http://www.heroism.org/class/1980/adamson.htm |website=Heroism |accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|first=Gail |last=Ablow |authorlink=   |title= Making Change: Rebecca Adamson  |publisher=[[Bill Moyers Journal]]|date=May 16, 2017 |url=https://billmoyers.com/story/making-change-rebecca-adamson/  |accessdate=}}</ref> where she learned about the history and culture of her Cherokee people.<ref name=\"Native Americans Today\">{{Cite book|first= Bruce Elliott|last= Johansen|authorlink=   |title= Native Americans Today: A Biographical Dictionary |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]]|location=Santa Barbara, California|date=June 22, 2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9FwyiW4rAD0C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=adamson&f=false  |accessdate=|ISBN=9780313355547|pages=4\u20137}}</ref> She holds a master of science in economic development from the [[Southern New Hampshire University]] in [[Manchester, New Hampshire]], where she teaches a graduate course on indigenous economics.<ref name=Dartmouth />\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduating from Firestone High School in Akron in 1967, she studied philosophy at the University of Akron and then took courses in law and economics at Piedmont College in Georgia.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith College Special Collections |title=Guide to the Rebecca Adamson papers |url=https://findingaids.smith.edu/repositories/2/resources/936 |website=Smith College Finding Aids |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> Adamson left college in 1970 to work on western reservations to help end the practice of removing Native American children from their homes and placing them in government or missionary-ran boarding schools in the hope of destroying their connections to their native languages and cultures.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://edu.lva.virginia.gov/changemakers/items/show/127|title=Virginia Women in History 2002 Rebecca Adamson|website=www.lva.virginia.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1972-1976, she was a member of the board of directors of [[Denver]], Colorado's Coalition of Indian-Controlled School Boards, where she worked toward synthesizing and facilitating policy reform at the national level.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The Native North American Almanac|last=Champagne|first=Duane|publisher=Gale Group|year=2001|isbn=0787616559|location=Farmington Hills, MI|pages=1174\u20131175}}</ref> The Coalition worked to \"wrest control of Indian schools from the U.S. government and Christian religious groups that had been running them for more than 100 years.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith College Special Collections |title=Guide to the Rebecca Adamson papers |url=https://findingaids.smith.edu/repositories/2/resources/936 |website=Smith College Finding Aids |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> Her work contributed to the [[Indian Self-Determination Act]] of 1975.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1982, she became founder and president of [[First Nations Development Institute]] in [[Falmouth, Virginia|Falmouth]], Virginia to promote economic development by founding commercial enterprises on reservations. In 1986, she served as an adviser on rural development for the [[United Nations]] (UN) during their Decade of Women. She became the adviser for the UN's International Labor Organization International Indigenous Rights from 1988-1989. She has also served on the board of directors for the National Center for Enterprise Development and the [[Council on Foundations]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1992, she became an adviser for the Catholic Conference's [[Catholic Campaign for Human Development|Campaign for Human Development]]. She has also served on the President's Council on Sustainable Development/Sustainable Communities Task Force.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHer work led to the first [[microcredit|microloan]] fund in the United States associated with a reservation, the first tribal investment model. This was a national movement for reservation land reform, and legislation on federal trust responsibility for Native Americans.<ref name=Dartmouth />\n\nAdamson's international work created the Lumba Aboriginal Community Foundation in [[Australia]]. It enabled the [[Bushmen|Sans Tribe]] to secure its traditional homelands in [[Botswana]], [[Namibia]], and southern Africa. She launched a strategy (that includes [[Alcoa]], [[Texaco]], [[Rio Tinto Group|Rio Tinto]], [[Merck Group|Merck]], [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]], and [[Occidental Petroleum|Occidental]]) with investment criteria that protect the rights of indigenous peoples and has been adopted by a [[mutual fund]], an [[index fund]], and [[Investment Advisor|investment advisors]].<ref name=Dartmouth />\n\nShe established a scholarship program for native people at the [[Yale School of Management|Yale School of Organization and Management]] and at the [[Carlson School of Management]] at the [[University of Minnesota]].  She convinced the [[World Bank]] to create the First Global Indigenous Peoples' Facility Fund to make small building grants.<ref name=Dartmouth />\n\nShe was appointed by the [[Obama Administration|Obama administration]] to serve a three year term on the U.S. Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative Advisory Committee to increase the transparency in the reporting on [[natural resource]] extraction.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|first=Gale Courey |last=Toensing |authorlink=   |title=  Rebecca Adamson Has a Plan for Empowering Indigenous Peoples |publisher=[[Indian Country Today]]|date=March 13, 2015 |url=https://newsmaven.io/indiancountrytoday/archive/rebecca-adamson-has-a-plan-for-empowering-indigenous-peoples-S0-O5BlruU6MrrMqKusvRw/  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nAdamson serves on the board of directors for the Calvert Social Investment Fund and the Calvert Small Cap Fund which are known for [[socially-responsible investing]] and co-founded a fund there. She is on the board and trustee for [[Tom's of Maine]], Inc. She is on the boards of [[Corporation for Enterprise Development]], The Bay Foundation, Josephine Bay Paul and C. Michael Paul Foundation, The [[Bridgespan Group]], and [[First Voice International]]. She is a founding member of Native Americans in Philanthropy, Funders Who Fund Native Americans, and International Funders for Indigenous Peoples.<ref name=\"Dartmouth\" />. She has been a member of the editorial boards of Indian Country Today, Native Americas, and for Akwe:kon Journal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith College Special Collections |title=Guide to the Rebecca Adamson papers |url=https://findingaids.smith.edu/repositories/2/resources/936 |website=Smith College Finding Aids |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the [[Standing Rock Sioux]] asked her to develop and coordinate an investor engagement strategy to pressure the builders of the [[Dakota Access Pipeline]] to change the planned route which was to pass near a river used for potable water near their reservation.<ref name=ForbesDAPL>{{Cite web|first=Morgan |last=Simon |authorlink=   |title=We're Not Done With DAPL: How Investors Can Still Support Indigenous Rights   |publisher=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|date=November 1, 2018 |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/morgansimon/2018/11/01/were-not-done-with-dapl-how-investors-can-still-support-indigenous-rights/#5da6a546e0d5 |accessdate=}}</ref> She was able to secure statements from [[Environmental, social and corporate governance|ESG]] investors with over $1.7 trillion in invested assets requesting that the banks funding the pipeline support the tribe's request to reroute the pipeline.<ref name=ForbesDAPL /> Her efforts helped to embolden activists who forced shareholder resolutions to require that the environmental and social risks were more adequately disclosed (including at [[Marathon Petroleum]], [[Enbridge]], and [[Wells Fargo]]) and encouraged over 500 [[NGO]]s to pressure the banks financing the pipeline with three major banks pulling out of the syndication ([[BNP Paribas]], [[DNB ASA]], and [[ING]]) and ten other banks supported strengthening the [[Equator Principles]].<ref name=ForbesDAPL />\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 1996, she was awarded the [[Robert W. Scribner|Robert W. Scrivner]] Award from the Council on Foundations for grant-making and the National Center for American Indian Enterprise Development's [[Jay Silverheels]] Award. [[Ms. (magazine)|''Ms.'' magazine]] named her one of their seven \"Women of the Year\" in 1997. In 1998, ''Who Cares'' magazine named her one of the top 10 Social Entrepreneurs of the Year.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2001 she was received the [[John W. Gardner|John W. Gardener]] Leadership Award.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2004, she was Scwab's Outstanding Social Entrepreneur.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2012, she was featured as one of the most influential women in America on [[PBS]]' ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America|MAKERS: Women Who Make America]]'' program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womensmediacenter.com/shesource/expert/rebecca-adamson|title=Rebecca Adamson - SheSource Expert - Women\u2019s Media Center|website=www.womensmediacenter.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref>\n\nShe writes a monthly column for ''[[Indian Country Today]]'' newspaper.<ref name=\"Dartmouth\" /> When asked about her accomplishments in 2015, she said, \"I come from a matrilineal society and having women be a source of power was there in my DNA.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Publications==\n*\"Adapting the Evaluation Process to the Organizational Culture,\" a chapter in Evaluation with Power, 1997\n*\"The Native American Credit Market: Opportunity Knocks, but Relationships Stay,\" RMA's Journal of Lending & Credit Risk Management, Fall 1997\n*\"Can't Give It Away Fast Enough? Try This,\" Foundation News & Commentary, January/February 1998\n*''The Color of Wealth \u2013 The Story behind the U.S. Racial Wealth Divide'', June 2006\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=15&v=VMV7NTO2o2Y Adamson on understanding sufficiency]\n*[https://www.tedmed.com/speakers/show?id=293061 Adamson's TEDMED profile]\n*[http://learningtogive.org/papers/paper175.html Biography at Learning to Give.]\n*[http://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss532_main.html Rebecca Adamson Papers]\n\n{{Virginia Women in History}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adamson, Rebecca}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American directors]]\n[[Category:Cherokee people]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:American women business executives]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:Southern New Hampshire University alumni]]\n[[Category:Southern New Hampshire University faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesswomen]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cherokee-American businessperson and activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rebecca Adamson\n| image              = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1950}}\n| birth_place        = [[Akron, Ohio]], United States\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[Americans|American]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Southern New Hampshire University]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Businesswoman, advocate\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = Founding First Peoples Worldwide\n| notable_works      = \n}}\n'''Rebecca Adamson''' (born 1950)<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography Center|url=https://nationalwomenshistoryalliance.org/biographies/|publisher=National Women's History Project|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref> is an [[United States|American]] [[Cherokee]] [[businessperson]] and [[advocate]]. She is former director, former president, and founder of [[First Nations Development Institute]] and the founder of First Peoples Worldwide.<ref name=Dartmouth>{{cite news|title=Dartmouth Honorary Degrees 2004:Rebecca L. Adamson|url=http://www.dartmouth.edu/~news/releases/2004/05/04a.html|publisher=Dartmouth News|accessdate=2009-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|first= |last= |authorlink=   |title=Rebecca Adamson papers, 1978-2007 (ongoing)  |publisher=[[Smith College]]|date= |url=https://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss532_main.html  |accessdate=August 10, 2019|quote=Economist, Founder First Nations Development Institute, Native American rights advocate. Papers are primarily related to her professional and public life, and focus on two organizations founded by Adamson, the First Nations Development Institute (FNDI) and First Peoples Worldwide (FPW).}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBorn in Akron, Ohio, to a Swedish American father and a Cherokee mother, Adamson grew up in Akron and spent summers with her Cherokee grandmother in [[Lumberton, North Carolina]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Rebecca Adamson |url=http://www.heroism.org/class/1980/adamson.htm |website=Heroism |accessdate=27 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|first=Gail |last=Ablow |authorlink=   |title= Making Change: Rebecca Adamson  |publisher=[[Bill Moyers Journal]]|date=May 16, 2017 |url=https://billmoyers.com/story/making-change-rebecca-adamson/  |accessdate=}}</ref> where she learned about the history and culture of her Cherokee people.<ref name=\"Native Americans Today\">{{Cite book|first= Bruce Elliott|last= Johansen|authorlink=   |title= Native Americans Today: A Biographical Dictionary |publisher=[[Greenwood Press]]|location=Santa Barbara, California|date=June 22, 2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9FwyiW4rAD0C&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=adamson&f=false  |accessdate=|ISBN=9780313355547|pages=4\u20137}}</ref> She holds a master of science in economic development from the [[Southern New Hampshire University]] in [[Manchester, New Hampshire]], where she teaches a graduate course on indigenous economics.<ref name=Dartmouth />\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduating from Firestone High School in Akron in 1967, she studied philosophy at the University of Akron and then took courses in law and economics at Piedmont College in Georgia.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith College Special Collections |title=Guide to the Rebecca Adamson papers |url=https://findingaids.smith.edu/repositories/2/resources/936 |website=Smith College Finding Aids |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> Adamson left college in 1970 to work on western reservations to help end the practice of removing Native American children from their homes and placing them in government or missionary-ran boarding schools in the hope of destroying their connections to their native languages and cultures.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://edu.lva.virginia.gov/changemakers/items/show/127|title=Virginia Women in History 2002 Rebecca Adamson|website=www.lva.virginia.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1972-1976, she was a member of the board of directors of [[Denver]], Colorado's Coalition of Indian-Controlled School Boards, where she worked toward synthesizing and facilitating policy reform at the national level.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=The Native North American Almanac|last=Champagne|first=Duane|publisher=Gale Group|year=2001|isbn=0787616559|location=Farmington Hills, MI|pages=1174\u20131175}}</ref> The Coalition worked to \"wrest control of Indian schools from the U.S. government and Christian religious groups that had been running them for more than 100 years.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith College Special Collections |title=Guide to the Rebecca Adamson papers |url=https://findingaids.smith.edu/repositories/2/resources/936 |website=Smith College Finding Aids |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> Her work contributed to the [[Indian Self-Determination Act]] of 1975.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 1982, she became founder and president of [[First Nations Development Institute]] in [[Falmouth, Virginia|Falmouth]], Virginia to promote economic development by founding commercial enterprises on reservations. In 1986, she served as an adviser on rural development for the [[United Nations]] (UN) during their Decade of Women. She became the adviser for the UN's International Labor Organization International Indigenous Rights from 1988-1989. She has also served on the board of directors for the National Center for Enterprise Development and the [[Council on Foundations]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1992, she became an adviser for the Catholic Conference's [[Catholic Campaign for Human Development|Campaign for Human Development]]. She has also served on the President's Council on Sustainable Development/Sustainable Communities Task Force.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHer work led to the first [[microcredit|microloan]] fund in the United States associated with a reservation, the first tribal investment model. This was a national movement for reservation land reform, and legislation on federal trust responsibility for Native Americans.<ref name=Dartmouth />\n\nAdamson's international work created the Lumba Aboriginal Community Foundation in [[Australia]]. It enabled the [[Bushmen|Sans Tribe]] to secure its traditional homelands in [[Botswana]], [[Namibia]], and southern Africa. She launched a strategy (that includes [[Alcoa]], [[Texaco]], [[Rio Tinto Group|Rio Tinto]], [[Merck Group|Merck]], [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]], and [[Occidental Petroleum|Occidental]]) with investment criteria that protect the rights of indigenous peoples and has been adopted by a [[mutual fund]], an [[index fund]], and [[Investment Advisor|investment advisors]].<ref name=Dartmouth />\n\nShe established a scholarship program for native people at the [[Yale School of Management|Yale School of Organization and Management]] and at the [[Carlson School of Management]] at the [[University of Minnesota]].  She convinced the [[World Bank]] to create the First Global Indigenous Peoples' Facility Fund to make small building grants.<ref name=Dartmouth />\n\nShe was appointed by the [[Obama Administration|Obama administration]] to serve a three year term on the U.S. Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative Advisory Committee to increase the transparency in the reporting on [[natural resource]] extraction.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|first=Gale Courey |last=Toensing |authorlink=   |title=  Rebecca Adamson Has a Plan for Empowering Indigenous Peoples |publisher=[[Indian Country Today]]|date=March 13, 2015 |url=https://newsmaven.io/indiancountrytoday/archive/rebecca-adamson-has-a-plan-for-empowering-indigenous-peoples-S0-O5BlruU6MrrMqKusvRw/  |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nAdamson serves on the board of directors for the Calvert Social Investment Fund and the Calvert Small Cap Fund which are known for [[socially-responsible investing]] and co-founded a fund there. She is on the board and trustee for [[Tom's of Maine]], Inc. She is on the boards of [[Corporation for Enterprise Development]], The Bay Foundation, Josephine Bay Paul and C. Michael Paul Foundation, The [[Bridgespan Group]], and [[First Voice International]]. She is a founding member of Native Americans in Philanthropy, Funders Who Fund Native Americans, and International Funders for Indigenous Peoples.<ref name=\"Dartmouth\" />. She has been a member of the editorial boards of Indian Country Today, Native Americas, and for Akwe:kon Journal.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Smith College Special Collections |title=Guide to the Rebecca Adamson papers |url=https://findingaids.smith.edu/repositories/2/resources/936 |website=Smith College Finding Aids |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the [[Standing Rock Sioux]] asked her to develop and coordinate an investor engagement strategy to pressure the builders of the [[Dakota Access Pipeline]] to change the planned route which was to pass near a river used for potable water near their reservation.<ref name=ForbesDAPL>{{Cite web|first=Morgan |last=Simon |authorlink=   |title=We're Not Done With DAPL: How Investors Can Still Support Indigenous Rights   |publisher=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]]|date=November 1, 2018 |url= https://www.forbes.com/sites/morgansimon/2018/11/01/were-not-done-with-dapl-how-investors-can-still-support-indigenous-rights/#5da6a546e0d5 |accessdate=}}</ref> She was able to secure statements from [[Environmental, social and corporate governance|ESG]] investors with over $1.7 trillion in invested assets requesting that the banks funding the pipeline support the tribe's request to reroute the pipeline.<ref name=ForbesDAPL /> Her efforts helped to embolden activists who forced shareholder resolutions to require that the environmental and social risks were more adequately disclosed (including at [[Marathon Petroleum]], [[Enbridge]], and [[Wells Fargo]]) and encouraged over 500 [[NGO]]s to pressure the banks financing the pipeline with three major banks pulling out of the syndication ([[BNP Paribas]], [[DNB ASA]], and [[ING]]) and ten other banks supported strengthening the [[Equator Principles]].<ref name=ForbesDAPL />\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 1996, she was awarded the [[Robert W. Scribner|Robert W. Scrivner]] Award from the Council on Foundations for grant-making and the National Center for American Indian Enterprise Development's [[Jay Silverheels]] Award. [[Ms. (magazine)|''Ms.'' magazine]] named her one of their seven \"Women of the Year\" in 1997. In 1998, ''Who Cares'' magazine named her one of the top 10 Social Entrepreneurs of the Year.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2001 she was received the [[John W. Gardner|John W. Gardener]] Leadership Award.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2004, she was Scwab's Outstanding Social Entrepreneur.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 2012, she was featured as one of the most influential women in America on [[PBS]]' ''[[Makers: Women Who Make America|MAKERS: Women Who Make America]]'' program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womensmediacenter.com/shesource/expert/rebecca-adamson|title=Rebecca Adamson - SheSource Expert - Women\u2019s Media Center|website=www.womensmediacenter.com|language=en|access-date=2018-11-01}}</ref>\n\nShe writes a monthly column for ''[[Indian Country Today]]'' newspaper.<ref name=\"Dartmouth\" /> When asked about her accomplishments in 2015, she said, \"I come from a matrilineal society and having women be a source of power was there in my DNA.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Publications==\n*\"Adapting the Evaluation Process to the Organizational Culture,\" a chapter in Evaluation with Power, 1997\n*\"The Native American Credit Market: Opportunity Knocks, but Relationships Stay,\" RMA's Journal of Lending & Credit Risk Management, Fall 1997\n*\"Can't Give It Away Fast Enough? Try This,\" Foundation News & Commentary, January/February 1998\n*''The Color of Wealth \u2013 The Story behind the U.S. Racial Wealth Divide'', June 2006\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=15&v=VMV7NTO2o2Y Adamson on understanding sufficiency]\n*[https://www.tedmed.com/speakers/show?id=293061 Adamson's TEDMED profile]\n*[http://learningtogive.org/papers/paper175.html Biography at Learning to Give.]\n*[http://asteria.fivecolleges.edu/findaids/sophiasmith/mnsss532_main.html Rebecca Adamson Papers]\n\n{{Virginia Women in History}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Adamson, Rebecca}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American directors]]\n[[Category:Cherokee people]]\n[[Category:American people of Swedish descent]]\n[[Category:American women business executives]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:Southern New Hampshire University alumni]]\n[[Category:Southern New Hampshire University faculty]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesswomen]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Shockofsputnik", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed duplicate and superseded citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rebecca_Adamson"}
{"title_page": "Ben Miles", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Ben Miles\n| image        =\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Benjamin Charles Miles\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1966|9|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Wimbledon, London]], England\n| nationality  = British\n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = 1989\u2013present\n| spouse       = Emily Raymond\n| children     = 3\n}}\n'''Benjamin Charles Miles''' (born 29 September 1966) is an English actor, best known for his starring role as Patrick Maitland in the television [[comedy]] ''[[Coupling (UK TV series)|Coupling]]'', from 2000 to 2004, as [[Peter Townsend (RAF officer)|Peter Townsend]] in the [[Netflix]] drama ''[[The Crown (TV series)|The Crown]]'' (2016\u20132017) and George in episode 8 \u201cThe One That Holds Everything\u201d in the TV drama ''[[The Romanoffs]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP refimprove|date=September 2018}}\nMiles was born in [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]], [[London]], and lived as a young man in [[Ashover]], [[Derbyshire]],<ref name=\"TDT\"/> attending [[Tupton Hall School]].  He began acting in school productions, which he pursued mainly because it allowed him to miss classes. In an interview, Miles stated how he would spend his spare time in a now-defunct record shop (Hudsons) in [[Chesterfield]], [[Derbyshire]] while \"thinking about 'finding the one'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/news/ben-miles-102490/|title=Ben Miles|date=15 Oct 2008|website=OfficialLondonTheatre.com|accessdate=30 Oct 2017}}</ref> He trained at the [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]]. \n\n==Career==\nHe moved into television roles in the 1990s, playing supporting roles in such series as ''[[Zorro (1990 TV series)|Zorro]]'', ''[[Soldier Soldier]]'', ''[[Is It Legal?]]'', ''[[The Bill]]'', ''[[Peak Practice]]'' and ''[[Wonderful You (TV series)|Wonderful You]]''.\n\nMiles played a very small part as a journalist, with just a few words of dialogue, in the 1997 [[motion picture]] ''[[The Wings of the Dove (1997 film)|The Wings of the Dove]]''. In 2000, he was cast as Robert Brown in [[Cold_Feet_(series_3)|Cold Feet]] and the womanizing [[Coupling (UK TV series)#Characters|Patrick Maitland]] in the comedy series ''[[Coupling (UK TV series)|Coupling]]'', a role which he played until the series ended in 2004. He continued other television work during his tenure in ''Coupling'', appearing in ''[[The Forsyte Saga (2002 miniseries)|The Forsyte Saga]]'' as Montague Dartie (this was the first time Miles acted with Amanda Root) and in ''[[Prime Suspect]]''. In 2004, Miles portrayed Charles Ryder in the [[BBC Radio 4]] production of ''[[Brideshead Revisited]]''. Miles was the co-lead in the [[BBC]] drama, ''A Thing Called Love'', filmed on location in Nottingham, England.\n\nMiles appeared in the 2005 [[BBC]] television drama ''[[Mr. Harvey Lights a Candle|Mr Harvey Lights a Candle]]'', playing the part of a teacher taking an unruly party of pupils on a daytrip to [[Salisbury Cathedral]]. In 2006, he appeared in the TV drama ''[[After Thomas]]'' as the father of a son with [[autism]].<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/theatre/article1726878.ece|title=Login|publisher=|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> He worked alongside actors such as [[Clive Mantle]]. In 2008, he appeared as the squire Sir Timothy in the British production ''[[Lark Rise to Candleford (TV series)|Lark Rise to Candleford]]'', and as Plantagenet Palliser in Radio 4 production ''The Pallisers''. In 2009, he appeared as the head of a stock market trading firm in the [[BBC]] city-based drama ''Sex, the City and Me''. He played the lead in ''Pulse'' opposite [[Claire Foy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a222366/ben-miles-bbc-three-show-defies-genre.html|title=Ben Miles: 'BBC Three show defies genre'|date=28 May 2010|publisher=|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> whom he also co-starred with in ''[[The Promise (2011 TV serial)|The Promise]]'' in early 2011, just after also appearing in [[BBC One|BBC 1]]'s ''[[Zen (TV series)|Zen]]''. They were re-united again in ''The Crown''.\n\nMiles often works with director [[James McTeigue]]: he appeared in McTeigue's 2005 film ''[[V for Vendetta (film)|V for Vendetta]]'' as Dascombe, in ''[[Ninja Assassin]],'' and in ''[[Speed Racer (film)|Speed Racer]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moviefone.com/news/|title=Entertainment, Movie & TV News - Moviefone.com|publisher=|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn stage, he played [[Henry IV of England|Bolingbroke]] in the [[Old Vic]]'s production of ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'' in 2005 alongside his father-in-law [[Gary Raymond]]. Miles also appeared in the play ''[[The Norman Conquests]]'' as Tom in 2009. ''The Norman Conquests'' won a [[Tony Award]] during his tenure in the play for [[Tony Award for Best Revival of a Play|Best Revival of a Play]].<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/131447-Exit-Laughing-Tony-Winning-Norman-Conquests-Ends-Broadway-Run Exit, Laughing: Tony-Winning Norman Conquests Ends Broadway Run] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826083316/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/131447-Exit-Laughing-Tony-Winning-Norman-Conquests-Ends-Broadway-Run |date=26 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn summer 2011, Miles starred as Robert in [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[Betrayal (play)|Betrayal]]'' at the [[Comedy Theatre]] in [[West End theatre|London's West End]], with [[Kristin Scott Thomas]] playing his wife, Emma. The love triangle was completed by [[Douglas Henshall]] as his best friend and her lover, Jerry. The revival was directed by [[Ian Rickson]]. Also in 2011 he appeared in the television film ''[[The Suspicions of Mr Whicher]]'' as Dr. Stapleton.\n\nIn 2014 Miles played Thomas Cromwell in the [[Royal Shakespeare Company|RSC]] version of [[Hilary Mantel]]'s novels ''[[Wolf Hall]]'' and ''[[Bring Up the Bodies]]'' in Stratford and at the [[Aldwych Theatre]] in London. In April 2015 the RSC brought the plays to New York City, where his performance was nominated for Best Leading Actor in a Play at the Tony Awards.<ref name=Soloski>{{cite news|last1=Soloski|first1=Alexis|title=Ben Miles Takes On \u2018Wolf Hall\u2019 Onstage|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/22/theater/ben-miles-takes-on-wolf-hall-onstage.html?_r=0|accessdate=23 March 2015|publisher=New York Times|date=18 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/epic-london-double-bill-wolf-hall-opens-on-broadway-346270|title=Epic London Double-Bill Wolf Hall Opens On Broadway - Playbill|publisher=|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he played [[Peter Townsend (RAF officer)|Peter Townsend]] in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[The Crown (TV series)|The Crown]]'', and the Duke of [[Edmund Beaufort, 2nd Duke of Somerset|Somerset]] in ''[[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown: The Wars of the Roses]]'', the second cycle in a series of television film adaptations of [[William Shakespeare]]'s history plays. In the same year, he also had a guest role as Chancellor Tom Pickering in an episode of the [[anthology series]] ''[[Black Mirror]]'' (\"[[Hated in the Nation]]\").\n\nIn 2017, he voiced the Time Traveller in a Big Finish Productions adaptation of ''[[The Time Machine]]'' and Ace in the UK dub of ''Bob the Builder: Mega Machines''.\n\nIn 2018, he played DSU Jack Haley in the [[BBC Two]] miniseries ''[[Collateral (miniseries)|Collateral]]'', Simon's father George Burrows in the series ''[[The Romanoffs]]'', and appeared on stage at the [[Lyttelton Theatre]] as one of the [[Lehman Brothers#Under the Lehman family (1850\u20131969)|Lehman Brothers]] in ''The Lehman Trilogy''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Treneman |first1=Anne |title=Magnificent Mendes tale of bank brothers is right on the money |work=The TImes |issue=72586 |date=13 July 2018 |page=23|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he played Commander Danny Hart in ''[[The Capture (TV series)|The Capture]]'' and [[John Profumo]] in ''[[ The Trial of Christine Keeler]]'', both on BBC One.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMiles can play bass, drums, and guitar and is left-handed. He is married to the actress Emily Raymond,<ref name=\"TDT\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Guy |title=The amount of privacy we give up is scary |work=The Daily Telegraph |issue=51,100 |date=3 September 2019 |page=20|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> who starred in the film ''[[Love Lies Bleeding (1999 film)|Love Lies Bleeding]]'' alongside [[Faye Dunaway]]; they have three children.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\"/> The two also appeared together in the episode of ''[[Peak Practice]]'', \"Before The Lights Go Out\" in 1999.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Getting It Right (film)|Getting It Right]]''\n| Spiro\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[The Wings of the Dove (1997 film)|The Wings of the Dove]]''\n| Journalist #1\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Keep the Aspidistra Flying (film)|Keep the Aspidistra Flying]]''\n| Ravenscroft Waiter\n| US Title: ''A Merry War''\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''Paris, Brixton''\n| Mike\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Affair of the Necklace]]''\n| Baron Courchamps\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Three Blind Mice (2003 film)|Three Blind Mice]]''\n| Lindsey\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[V for Vendetta (2006 film)|V for Vendetta]]''\n| Dascomb\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Speed Racer (film)|Speed Racer]]''\n| Cass Jones\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Ninja Assassin]]''\n| Maslow\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Harry VI: Part 1 - Deleted Scenes''\n| Somerset\n| Short film<br>Direct-to-video\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Bob the Builder: Mega Machines''\n| Ace (voice)\n| UK version\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Catcher Was a Spy (film)|The Catcher Was a Spy]]''\n| Jerry Fredericks\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Red Joan]]''\n| Nick\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''The Lehman Trilogy''\n|\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n| 2000\u20132004\n| ''[[Coupling (British TV series)|Coupling]]''\n| Patrick Maitland\n| 28 episodes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Holby City]]''\n| Ed Somers\n| Episode: \"Tip of the Iceberg\"\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[The Government Inspector (film)|The Government Inspector]]''\n| Kevin Marsh\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Lark Rise to Candleford (TV series)|Lark Rise to Candleford]]''\n| Sir Timothy Midwinter\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Pulse''\n| Joe Sennet\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Zen (TV series)|Zen]]''\n| Amedeo Colonna\n| 3 episodes<br>Television miniseries\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Promise (2011 TV serial)|The Promise]]''\n| Max Meyer\n| 4 episodes<br>Television miniseries\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Suspicions of Mr Whicher]]''\n| Dr. Stapleton\n| Episode: \"The Murder at Road Hill House\"\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Masterpiece Mystery''\n| Amedeo Colonna\n| Episode: \"Ratking\"\n|-\n| 2013\u20132014\n| ''[[Dracula (2013 TV series)|Dracula]]''\n| Browning\n| 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017\n| ''[[The Crown (TV series)|The Crown]]''\n| [[Peter Townsend (RAF officer)|Peter Townsend]]\n| 9 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\u20132018\n| ''[[Bob the Builder]]''\n| Ace (voice)\n| UK version<br>4 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Collateral (TV series)|Collateral]]''\n| DSU Jack Haley\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Romanoffs]]''\n| George Burrows\n| Episode: \"The One That Holds Everything\"\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Capture (TV series)|The Capture]]''\n| Commander Daniel \"Danny\" Hart\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\u20132020\n| ''[[The Trial of Christine Keeler]]''\n| [[John Profumo]]\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The One Show]]''\n| Himself\n| One episode\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Mare of Easttown]]''\n| Richard Ryan\n| Episode: \"#1.1\"\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0587060|name=Ben Miles}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/comedy/coupling/cast/ben_miles.shtml Ben Miles profile] from [[BBC]]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/pressoffice/pressreleases/stories/2007/12_december/17/lark_miles.shtml Lark Rise to Candleford] from [[BBC]]\n* [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/8581570/Betrayal-Comedy-Theatre-review.html Betrayal, \"Comedy Theatre Review\"],  ''The Telegraph'', 17 June 2011\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/jun/17/betrayal-review Betrayal - Review, \"Comedy Theatre London\"],  ''The Guardian'', 17 June 2011\n* [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/first-night-betrayal-comedy-theatre-london-2298827.html First Night: Betrayal, \"Comedy Theatre London\"],  ''The Independent'', 17 June 2011\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Miles, Ben}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Guildhall School of Music and Drama]]\n[[Category:20th-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century English male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:People from Wimbledon, London]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2016}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Ben Miles\n| image        =\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Benjamin Charles Miles\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1966|9|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Wimbledon, London]], England\n| nationality  = British\n| occupation   = Actor\n| years_active = 1989\u2013present\n| spouse       = Emily Raymond\n| children     = 3\n}}\n'''Benjamin Charles Miles''' (born 29 September 1966) is an English actor, best known for his starring role as Patrick Maitland in the television [[comedy]] ''[[Coupling (UK TV series)|Coupling]]'', from 2000 to 2004, as [[Peter Townsend (RAF officer)|Peter Townsend]] in the [[Netflix]] drama ''[[The Crown (TV series)|The Crown]]'' (2016\u20132017) and George in episode 8 \u201cThe One That Holds Everything\u201d in the TV drama ''[[The Romanoffs]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life==\n{{BLP refimprove|date=September 2018}}\nMiles was born in [[Wimbledon, London|Wimbledon]], [[London]], and lived as a young man in [[Ashover]], [[Derbyshire]],<ref name=\"TDT\"/> attending [[Tupton Hall School]].  He began acting in school productions, which he pursued mainly because it allowed him to miss classes. In an interview, Miles stated how he would spend his spare time in a now-defunct record shop (Hudsons) in [[Chesterfield]], [[Derbyshire]] while \"thinking about 'finding the one'\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://officiallondontheatre.com/news/ben-miles-102490/|title=Ben Miles|date=15 Oct 2008|website=OfficialLondonTheatre.com|accessdate=30 Oct 2017}}</ref> He trained at the [[Guildhall School of Music and Drama]]. \n\n==Career==\nHe moved into television roles in the 1990s, playing supporting roles in such series as ''[[Zorro (1990 TV series)|Zorro]]'', ''[[Soldier Soldier]]'', ''[[Is It Legal?]]'', ''[[The Bill]]'', ''[[Peak Practice]]'' and ''[[Wonderful You (TV series)|Wonderful You]]''.\n\nMiles played a very small part as a journalist, with just a few words of dialogue, in the 1997 [[motion picture]] ''[[The Wings of the Dove (1997 film)|The Wings of the Dove]]''. In 2000, he was cast as Robert Brown in [[Cold_Feet_(series_3)|Cold Feet]] and the womanizing [[Coupling (UK TV series)#Characters|Patrick Maitland]] in the comedy series ''[[Coupling (UK TV series)|Coupling]]'', a role which he played until the series ended in 2004. He continued other television work during his tenure in ''Coupling'', appearing in ''[[The Forsyte Saga (2002 miniseries)|The Forsyte Saga]]'' as Montague Dartie (this was the first time Miles acted with Amanda Root) and in ''[[Prime Suspect]]''. In 2004, Miles portrayed Charles Ryder in the [[BBC Radio 4]] production of ''[[Brideshead Revisited]]''. Miles was the co-lead in the [[BBC]] drama, ''A Thing Called Love'', filmed on location in Nottingham, England.\n\nMiles appeared in the 2005 [[BBC]] television drama ''[[Mr. Harvey Lights a Candle|Mr Harvey Lights a Candle]]'', playing the part of a teacher taking an unruly party of pupils on a daytrip to [[Salisbury Cathedral]]. In 2006, he appeared in the TV drama ''[[After Thomas]]'' as the father of a son with [[autism]].<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/stage/theatre/article1726878.ece|title=Login|publisher=|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> He worked alongside actors such as [[Clive Mantle]]. In 2008, he appeared as the squire Sir Timothy in the British production ''[[Lark Rise to Candleford (TV series)|Lark Rise to Candleford]]'', and as Plantagenet Palliser in Radio 4 production ''The Pallisers''. In 2009, he appeared as the head of a stock market trading firm in the [[BBC]] city-based drama ''Sex, the City and Me''. He played the lead in ''Pulse'' opposite [[Claire Foy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a222366/ben-miles-bbc-three-show-defies-genre.html|title=Ben Miles: 'BBC Three show defies genre'|date=28 May 2010|publisher=|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref> whom he also co-starred with in ''[[The Promise (2011 TV serial)|The Promise]]'' in early 2011, just after also appearing in [[BBC One|BBC 1]]'s ''[[Zen (TV series)|Zen]]''. They were re-united again in ''The Crown''.\n\nMiles often works with director [[James McTeigue]]: he appeared in McTeigue's 2005 film ''[[V for Vendetta (film)|V for Vendetta]]'' as Dascombe, in ''[[Ninja Assassin]],'' and in ''[[Speed Racer (film)|Speed Racer]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moviefone.com/news/|title=Entertainment, Movie & TV News - Moviefone.com|publisher=|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn stage, he played [[Henry IV of England|Bolingbroke]] in the [[Old Vic]]'s production of ''[[Richard II (play)|Richard II]]'' in 2005 alongside his father-in-law [[Gary Raymond]]. Miles also appeared in the play ''[[The Norman Conquests]]'' as Tom in 2009. ''The Norman Conquests'' won a [[Tony Award]] during his tenure in the play for [[Tony Award for Best Revival of a Play|Best Revival of a Play]].<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/131447-Exit-Laughing-Tony-Winning-Norman-Conquests-Ends-Broadway-Run Exit, Laughing: Tony-Winning Norman Conquests Ends Broadway Run] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826083316/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/131447-Exit-Laughing-Tony-Winning-Norman-Conquests-Ends-Broadway-Run |date=26 August 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn summer 2011, Miles starred as Robert in [[Harold Pinter]]'s ''[[Betrayal (play)|Betrayal]]'' at the [[Comedy Theatre]] in [[West End theatre|London's West End]], with [[Kristin Scott Thomas]] playing his wife, Emma. The love triangle was completed by [[Douglas Henshall]] as his best friend and her lover, Jerry. The revival was directed by [[Ian Rickson]]. Also in 2011 he appeared in the television film ''[[The Suspicions of Mr Whicher]]'' as Dr. Stapleton.\n\nIn 2014 Miles played Thomas Cromwell in the [[Royal Shakespeare Company|RSC]] version of [[Hilary Mantel]]'s novels ''[[Wolf Hall]]'' and ''[[Bring Up the Bodies]]'' in Stratford and at the [[Aldwych Theatre]] in London. In April 2015 the RSC brought the plays to New York City, where his performance was nominated for Best Leading Actor in a Play at the Tony Awards.<ref name=Soloski>{{cite news|last1=Soloski|first1=Alexis|title=Ben Miles Takes On \u2018Wolf Hall\u2019 Onstage|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/22/theater/ben-miles-takes-on-wolf-hall-onstage.html?_r=0|accessdate=23 March 2015|publisher=New York Times|date=18 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/epic-london-double-bill-wolf-hall-opens-on-broadway-346270|title=Epic London Double-Bill Wolf Hall Opens On Broadway - Playbill|publisher=|accessdate=6 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, he played [[Peter Townsend (RAF officer)|Peter Townsend]] in the [[Netflix]] series ''[[The Crown (TV series)|The Crown]]'', and the Duke of [[Edmund Beaufort, 2nd Duke of Somerset|Somerset]] in ''[[The Hollow Crown (TV series)|The Hollow Crown: The Wars of the Roses]]'', the second cycle in a series of television film adaptations of [[William Shakespeare]]'s history plays. In the same year, he also had a guest role as Chancellor Tom Pickering in an episode of the [[anthology series]] ''[[Black Mirror]]'' (\"[[Hated in the Nation]]\").\n\nIn 2017, he voiced the Time Traveller in a Big Finish Productions adaptation of ''[[The Time Machine]]'' and Ace in the UK dub of ''Bob the Builder: Mega Machines''.\n\nIn 2018, he played DSU Jack Haley in the [[BBC Two]] miniseries ''[[Collateral (miniseries)|Collateral]]'', Simon's father George Burrows in the series ''[[The Romanoffs]]'', and appeared on stage at the [[Lyttelton Theatre]] as one of the [[Lehman Brothers#Under the Lehman family (1850\u20131969)|Lehman Brothers]] in ''The Lehman Trilogy''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Treneman |first1=Anne |title=Magnificent Mendes tale of bank brothers is right on the money |work=The TImes |issue=72586 |date=13 July 2018 |page=23|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019 he played Commander Danny Hart in ''[[The Capture (TV series)|The Capture]]'' and [[John Profumo]] in ''[[ The Trial of Christine Keeler]]'', both on BBC One.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMiles can play bass, drums, and guitar and is left-handed. He is married to the actress Emily Raymond,<ref name=\"TDT\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Guy |title=The amount of privacy we give up is scary |work=The Daily Telegraph |issue=51,100 |date=3 September 2019 |page=20|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> who starred in the film ''[[Love Lies Bleeding (1999 film)|Love Lies Bleeding]]'' alongside [[Faye Dunaway]]; they have three children.<ref name=\"timesonline.co.uk\"/> The two also appeared together in the episode of ''[[Peak Practice]]'', \"Before The Lights Go Out\" in 1999.{{cn|date=September 2018}}\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n| 1989\n| ''[[Getting It Right (film)|Getting It Right]]''\n| Spiro\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[The Wings of the Dove (1997 film)|The Wings of the Dove]]''\n| Journalist #1\n|\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''[[Keep the Aspidistra Flying (film)|Keep the Aspidistra Flying]]''\n| Ravenscroft Waiter\n| US Title: ''A Merry War''\n|-\n| 1997\n| ''Paris, Brixton''\n| Mike\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[The Affair of the Necklace]]''\n| Baron Courchamps\n|\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''[[Three Blind Mice (2003 film)|Three Blind Mice]]''\n| Lindsey\n|\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[V for Vendetta (2006 film)|V for Vendetta]]''\n| Dascomb\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Speed Racer (film)|Speed Racer]]''\n| Cass Jones\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Ninja Assassin]]''\n| Maslow\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Harry VI: Part 1 - Deleted Scenes''\n| Somerset\n| Short film<br>Direct-to-video\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Bob the Builder: Mega Machines''\n| Ace (voice)\n| UK version\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Catcher Was a Spy (film)|The Catcher Was a Spy]]''\n| Jerry Fredericks\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Red Joan]]''\n| Nick\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''The Lehman Trilogy''\n|\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n| 2000\u20132004\n| ''[[Coupling (British TV series)|Coupling]]''\n| Patrick Maitland\n| 28 episodes\n|-\n| 2001\n| ''[[Holby City]]''\n| Ed Somers\n| Episode: \"Tip of the Iceberg\"\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[The Government Inspector (film)|The Government Inspector]]''\n| Kevin Marsh\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Pulse''\n| Joe Sennet\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Zen (TV series)|Zen]]''\n| Amedeo Colonna\n| 3 episodes<br>Television miniseries\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[The Promise (2011 TV serial)|The Promise]]''\n| Max Meyer\n| 4 episodes