{"title_page": "2019 Wigan Warriors season", "text_new": "{{lead missing|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox rugby league team season\n | name            = Wigan Warriors 2019 season\n | year            = 2019\n | team_colour     = #DC143C\n | font_colour     = White\n | league          = Super League\n | league_link     = [[Super League XXIV]]\n | league_rank     = 2nd\n | league_wins     = 18\n | league_draws    = 0\n | league_losses   = 11\n | points_for      = 699\n | points_against  = 539\n | playoff_result  = \n | cup             = Challenge Cup \n | cup_result      = 6th Round\n | cup_wins        = 0\n | cup_losses      = 1\n | CEO_title       = Chairman\n | CEO             = [[Ian Lenagan]] \n | coach_title     = Head Coach\n | coach           = [[Adrian Lam]]\n | captain        = [[Sean O'Loughlin]]\n | stadium         = [[DW Stadium]]\n | avg_attendance  = \n | high_attendance = \n | low_attendance  = \n | top_tries       = \n | top_goals       = \n | top_points      = \n | prev_season     = [[2018 Wigan Warriors season|2018]]\n | next_season     = [[2020 Wigan Warriors season|2020]]\n | list            = yes\n | list_link       = List of Wigan Warriors seasons\n| pattern_la1        = _red_hoops\n| pattern_b1         = _whitehoops\n| pattern_ra1        = _red_hoops\n| pattern_sh1        = \n| pattern_so1        = _hoops_red\n| leftarm1           = FFFFFF\n| body1              = DE0821\n| rightarm1          = FFFFF\n| shorts1            = FFFFF\n| socks1             = DE0821\n}}\n\nThe 2019 season saw '''[[Wigan Warriors]]''' compete in the [[Super League XXIV|Super League]], Grand Final Play offs, [[2019 Challenge Cup|Challenge Cup]], and the [[2019 World Club Challenge|World Club Challenge]].\n\n==World Club Challenge==\n{{main|2019 World Club Challenge}}\nWinners of the [[2018 Super League Grand Final]], Wigan Warriors qualified to play [[2018 NRL season|2018 NRL]] champions [[Sydney Roosters]] in the [[2019 World Club Challenge]]. Wigan were beaten by the Australian side, retaining the title for the NRL.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/47217076|title=Wigan Warriors 8-20 Sydney Roosters: NRL side win World Club Challenge|date=February 17, 2019|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n!Date\n!Opponent\n!H/A\n!Result\n!Scorers\n!Att.\n|- style=\"background:#ffdddd\n|17th February 2019\n|{{leagueicon|Sydney|16}} [[Sydney Roosters]]\n|H\n|8\u201320\n| \n|21,331\n|-\n|}\n\n==Super League==\n{{main|Super League XXIV}}\n\n====Matches====\nWigan's form was split through the season. The previous year's [[2018 Super League Grand Final|Grand Final]] champions start the season in poor form winning only once in their first six games. Form improved towards the middle of the season, before a surge of good results towards the end of the season \u2013 losing only once in the last three months. Wigan finished second in the league for the second year in a row.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seriousaboutrl.com/bounce-back-wigan-warriors-2019-season-review-23571/|title=Bounce Back?! Wigan Warriors 2019 Season Review|date=October 23, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-league/teams/wigan/scores-fixtures|title=Wigan Warriors - Scores & Fixtures - Rugby League|website=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n!Date\n!Opponent\n!H/A\n!Result\n!Scorers\n!Att.\n!Pos.\n|- style=\"background:#ffdddd;\"\n| 31 January 2019\n| {{leagueicon|st Helens|16}} [[St Helens RFC|St Helens]]\n| [[Totally Wicked Stadium|A]]\n| 22\u201312\n| \n| 16'508\n|\n|- style=\"background:#ddffdd;\"\n| 8 February 2019\n| {{leagueicon|Leeds|16}} [[Leeds Rhinos]]\n| H\n| 34\u201316\n| \n| 11,230\n| \n|- style=\"background:#ffdddd;\"\n| 24 February 2019\n| {{leagueicon| Hull|16}} [[Hull F.C.]]\n| H\n| 22\u201323\n| \n| 10,971\n|  \n|- style=\"background:#ffdddd;\"\n| 3 March 2019\n| {{leagueicon|London|16}} [[London Broncos]]\n| [[Trailfinders Sports Gr